[See arena.h, arena.c, pool.h, pool.c]

This project relies on multiple different allocators, each specialized for their purpose.
These are: Arena allocator, Pool (reference objects), and the system allocator.

For instance, compilation uses an arena (bump) allocator for temporary allocations.

1. Arena allocator:
* The arena allocator simply allocates a block of E_PAGESIZE memory,
* It stores a "head" variable to track where the next allocation will start.
* When you allocate from the arena, it returns a pointer in the page starting from head,
* aligning it to E_ARENA_MINIMUM_ALIGNMENT, returning it.
* It then moves the head forward by the number of bytes allocated.
* No free function is present! All pages are cleared on e_arena_free().

2. Pool allocator:
* Used for referenced objects.
* Stores "branches" per type size.
* When some type size needs to be allocated,
* the pool finds the bucket with the best fit size and returns
* a branch from there (allocating another branch if needed).

3. System allocator: Used for everything else, resizable arrays (faster performance), et cetera.